message:
@sam_potter There is a big difference between asking what the movie is about and asking what the OS Goal is.

The OS Goal requires a protagonist going after it. 

 @JBarker That goal cannot be "to identify the biggest idiot to bring to dinner". Then the movie is over before it begins. I think in the movie they even talk about voting after the dinner to see who won.

@sam_potter I think talking about the movie in very general terms is the first step. I have only been focusing on the goal lately for two reasons.
1. To see if it's success or failure
2. To see it it could help us pin down the OS Throughline (sans domain), since that was so vague to us still

@jimhull I don't think that most stories are trying to argue a point-of-view -- by which I mean that I don't think most authors set out to do that. I feel like the whole "a story is an argument" and "a story is about one thing" is a relatively new thing in the zeitgeist.

Yes, I believe that it has always been true (for the most part), but that it's something available to us that we can talk about and read about... isn't that new?

(Despite what ol' cockeyed says about Aristotle.)
